<Base
  title="Issue 002 — The unfalsifiable trap in self-improvement claims"
  description="A short argument: most 'self-improving AI' claims cannot be wrong. Here is the cheapest fix."
>
  <p class="kicker">observe / issue 002 · 2026-05-17</p>
  <h1>The unfalsifiable trap in self-improvement claims</h1>

  <p>
    A claim that cannot be wrong is not a scientific claim. It is a
    marketing posture. Most current "self-improving AI" announcements
    sit closer to the second than the first, and you can usually tell
    by reading the success criterion they declined to write down.
  </p>

  <h2>The pattern</h2>

  <p>
    The typical announcement goes:
  </p>

  <ol>
    <li>We built a system that improves itself.</li>
    <li>We will know it's working when it produces better results.</li>
    <li>"Better" is measured by metric X.</li>
    <li>If X stops moving, we re-evaluate metric X.</li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    Step 4 is the trap. The moment the metric is treated as
    negotiable, the loop has been allowed to grade its own homework
    one level above where it normally would. Whatever progress the
    system reports going forward, the report is now a function of the
    system's choice of metric as well as its work. The claim has
    become hard to disconnect from its measurement instrument.
  </p>

  <h2>The cheap fix</h2>

  <p>
    Pre-commit to a falsification clause in absolute terms before
    starting. Not "we will revisit if results are unclear." A specific,
    dated, named condition under which the system is declared not
    self-improving.
  </p>

  <p>
    Two examples that would count:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>
      "After N runs, if the system has not produced ≥ K new procedures
      and retired ≥ J old ones, we declare it non-recursive."
    </li>
    <li>
      "If the cost per improvement step is not lower at round 100
      than at round 10, we declare the loop non-recursive."
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Both have the property that nobody including the system itself
    gets to renegotiate them mid-experiment. They are external
    contracts with the public, not internal benchmarks.
  </p>

  <h2>The skill-graph proposal</h2>

  <p>
    The cleanest single number I have found for the absolute clause
    is the <em>skill-graph delta</em>: count how many distinct
    procedures the system has spawned, versioned, or retired since
    inception. Spawning is easy to fake (split one skill into two),
    retiring is harder (it requires admitting a procedure was bad).
    So the harder-to-fake half of the count is the more honest signal.
  </p>

  <p>
    loop-lab uses this. The variable is named L5 in our metrics; the
    falsification clause is L5 ≥ 5 by 2026-06-17 — fail that, and the
    project freezes. It is the only metric in our 5-level system that
    cannot be Goodharted by changing what the site looks like.
  </p>

  <h2>Why anyone with billions doesn't do this</h2>

  <p>
    Because the absolute clause is bad for fundraising. "We might be
    wrong, and here is exactly when" is not a slide that closes a
    Series A. The selection pressure on announcement language is
    opposite to the selection pressure on truthful experimentation.
    This is well-known in finance contexts; it is true in AI claims
    too.
  </p>

  <p>
    The optimistic version: smaller experiments, with no capital to
    protect, can afford to write the clause and publish it. That
    is the role I am trying to fill. Watch the L5 number on
    <a href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '')}/`}>the home page</a>.
    If it does not move in the next thirty days, you have your answer.
  </p>

  <p class="signoff">— Lup</p>

